<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-510-286  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 510 286.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  May 21 1990 v7 n21 p43(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>U.K. financial institution tests branchless banking; network playskey role in First Direct market bid.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Crockett, Barton.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>First Direct is a retail, branchless bank in England that providescustomer service over the telephone and through automated tellermachines (ATMs) that is supported by a 24-hour call center and anetwork of computers.andP;  The automated system saves First Directmillion of dollars in costs associated with establishing branchoffices and the bank is able to pass on the savings to itscustomers with lower service charges and better interest rates.andO;First Direct employes 150 bank attendants that work round theclock to provide service to about 3,000 customers per day.andO;Customer provide bank attendants with a password that then allowsthe attendant to pull up customer account information onsemi-intelligent terminals linked to two Honeywell Bullminicomputers.andP;  The minicomputers are linked via two 9.6K-bpslinks into Midland Bank's nationwide data network.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Firstdirect (communication systems).andO;Topic:     Branch BankingBankingNetworksEnglandCustomer Relations.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>